      "account_id" : 196747,
      "reputation" : 10620,
      "user_id" : 440355,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 67,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5ef782cc63799dfcd576190f0f078082?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jean",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/440355/jean"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 565,
    "last_activity_date" : 1525617692,
    "last_edit_date" : 1525617692,
    "creation_date" : 1287033064,
    "answer_id" : 3930249,
    "question_id" : 3930210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html#toString--\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Integer.toString</code></a> calls the static method in the class <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Integer</code></a>. It does not need an instance of <code>Integer</code>.</p>\n\n<p>If you call <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Integer.html#Integer-int-\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>new Integer(i)</code></a> you create an instance of type <code>Integer</code>, which is a full Java object encapsulating the value of your int. Then you call the <code>toString</code> method on it to ask it to return a string representation of <em>itself</em>.</p>\n\n<p>If all you want is to print an <code>int</code>, you'd use the first one because it's lighter, faster and doesn't use extra memory (aside from the returned string).  </p>\n\n<p>If you want an object representing an integer value—to put it inside a collection for example—you'd use the second one, since it gives you a full-fledged object to do all sort of things that you cannot do with a bare <code>int</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 155900,
      "reputation" : 4365,
      "user_id" : 372860,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 91,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/809841ad95d2db532aeb0b62e6a0d129?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "oksayt",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/372860/oksayt"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 97,
    "last_activity_date" : 1405692497,
    "last_edit_date" : 1405692497,
    "creation_date" : 1287033136,
    "answer_id" : 3930255,
    "question_id" : 3930210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>new Integer(i).toString()</code> first creates a (redundant) wrapper object around <code>i</code> (which itself may be a wrapper object <code>Integer</code>).</p>\n\n<p><code>Integer.toString(i)</code> is preferred because it doesn't create any unnecessary objects.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 218826,
      "reputation" : 350,
      "user_id" : 475352,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6f38064300e400c100ae67b46a9ea1be?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Dhiraj",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/475352/dhiraj"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 14,
    "last_activity_date" : 1509883715,
    "last_edit_date" : 1592644375,
    "creation_date" : 1287034525,
    "answer_id" : 3930358,
    "question_id" : 3930210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<ol>\n<li><p><code>new Integer(i).toString();</code></p>\n<p>This statement creates the object of the Integer and then call its methods <code>toString(i)</code> to <strong>return the String representation of Integer's value</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p><code>Integer.toString(i);</code></p>\n<p>It <strong>returns the String object representing the specific int (integer)</strong>, but here <code>toString(int)</code> is a <code>static</code> method.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Summary is in first case it returns the objects string representation, where as in second case it returns the string representation of integer.</p>\n"
  }, {
